{
  "In quantum mechanics, eigenvalues of an observable operator represent:": "",
  "The probabilities of measurement outcomes": "",
  "The possible measurement outcomes": "",
  "The time evolution rates": "",
  "The wave function amplitudes": "",
  "In quantum mechanics, eigenvalues of an Hermitian operator correspond to the possible measurement outcomes. The eigenvectors are the corresponding eigenstates.": "",
  "The moment of inertia tensor I for a rigid body has eigenvalues called:": "",
  "Angular velocities": "",
  "Principal moments of inertia": "",
  "Torque components": "",
  "Rotation angles": "",
  "The eigenvalues of the inertia tensor are the principal moments of inertia, and the eigenvectors define the principal axes of rotation about which the body rotates freely.": "",
  "In a coupled oscillator system, the eigenvalues of the stiffness matrix determine:": "",
  "The damping coefficients": "",
  "The normal mode frequencies (squared)": "",
  "The total energy of the system": "",
  "The equilibrium positions": "",
  "For M*x'' + K*x = 0, the eigenvalues of M^(-1)K give omega^2 for each normal mode. The eigenvectors give the shapes of the normal modes.": "",
  "The Pauli spin matrices are 2x2 Hermitian matrices. What are the eigenvalues of any Pauli matrix?": "",
  "+1/2 and -1/2": "",
  "0 and 1": "",
  "+1 and -1": "",
  "i and -i": "",
  "All three Pauli matrices (sigma_x, sigma_y, sigma_z) have eigenvalues +1 and -1. These correspond to spin-up and spin-down states along the respective axis.": "",
  "For a symmetric stress tensor, what do the eigenvalues represent?": "",
  "Principal stresses (normal stresses on principal planes)": "",
  "Young's modulus values under normal circumstances": "",
  "Strain rates, particularly regarding where": "",
  "Shear stresses, particularly regarding": "",
  "The eigenvalues of the stress tensor are the principal stresses, the pure normal stresses acting on planes where shear stress is zero. The eigenvectors give the principal directions.": "",
  "A quantum system is in state |psi> = (3/5)|+> + (4/5)|->. If |+> and |-> are eigenstates of an operator with eigenvalues +1 and -1, what is the expectation value?": "",
  "7/25": "",
  "0": "",
  "-7/25": "",
  "1/5": "",
  "The expectation value is sum of (probability)(eigenvalue): (3/5)^2(+1) + (4/5)^2(-1) = 9/25 - 16/25 = -7/25.": "",
  "The eigenvalues of a rotation matrix in 3D about an axis by angle theta are:": "",
  "1, e^(i*theta), e^(-i*theta)": "",
  "cos(theta), sin(theta), 1": "",
  "theta, -theta, 0": "",
  "1, 1, 1": "",
  "A 3D rotation has one real eigenvalue 1 (the rotation axis) and a complex conjugate pair e^(+/-i*theta). The eigenvector for eigenvalue 1 points along the axis of rotation.": "",
  "For a conservative force field F = -grad(V), the Hessian of V at a minimum has what property for its eigenvalues?": "",
  "All eigenvalues are positive": "",
  "All eigenvalues are zero": "",
  "Eigenvalues have mixed signs": "",
  "All eigenvalues are negative": "",
  "At a local minimum of the potential V, the Hessian is positive definite (all eigenvalues positive). This corresponds to restoring forces in all directions.": "",
  "In special relativity, the Lorentz transformation preserves a quadratic form with signature (+,-,-,-). What are the eigenvalues of a Lorentz boost matrix?": "",
  "v/c and -v/c, particularly": "",
  "1 and -1, particularly regarding": "",
  "e^phi and e^(-phi) where phi is the rapidity": "",
  "gamma and 1/gamma in accordance": "",
  "A Lorentz boost in the t-x plane has eigenvalues e^(phi) and e^(-phi) where tanh(phi) = v/c. The eigenvectors are along the light-cone directions (t +/- x).": "",
  "The eigenvalues of the quantum harmonic oscillator Hamiltonian are:": "",
  "n*h*omega for n = 0, 1, 2, ...": "",
  "Continuous spectrum from 0 to infinity": "",
  "n^2*h_bar*omega for n = 1, 2, 3, ...": "",
  "(n + 1/2)*h_bar*omega for n = 0, 1, 2, ...": "",
  "The quantum harmonic oscillator has equally spaced energy levels E_n = (n + 1/2) h_bar omega, where n = 0, 1, 2, .... The 1/2 represents the zero-point energy.": "",
  "What is a 'normal mode' in the physics of oscillating systems?": "",
  "A pattern of motion where all parts oscillate at the same frequency, corresponding to an eigenvector": "",
  "The average motion of the system": "",
  "Any oscillation perpendicular to the equilibrium": "",
  "The fastest possible oscillation": "",
  "A normal mode is a pattern of oscillation in which all parts of the system move sinusoidally at the same frequency. Each normal mode corresponds to an eigenvector of the system matrix.": "",
  "What are 'principal axes' in the context of the inertia tensor?": "",
  "The longest and shortest dimensions of the body": "",
  "Axes about which the body cannot rotate": "",
  "Directions (eigenvectors) along which rotation produces angular momentum parallel to angular velocity": "",
  "The x, y, z coordinate axes": "",
  "Principal axes are the eigenvectors of the inertia tensor. When a body rotates about a principal axis, L = I*omega is parallel to omega, meaning no torque is needed to maintain the rotation.": "",
  "What is the 'spectral decomposition' of a Hermitian operator in quantum mechanics?": "",
  "Decomposing the operator into a product of unitary matrices": "",
  "Finding the frequency spectrum of the operator": "",
  "Breaking the operator into real and imaginary parts": "",
  "Writing the operator as a sum of eigenvalue times projector onto the corresponding eigenspace": "",
  "The spectral decomposition writes A = sum of lambda_i |v_i><v_i|, expressing the operator as a weighted sum of projection operators onto its eigenstates.": "",
  "What is the physical meaning of a 'degenerate eigenvalue' in quantum mechanics?": "",
  "An energy level with no physical significance": "",
  "An eigenvalue with multiplicity greater than 1, meaning multiple distinct states share the same energy": "",
  "An eigenvalue that changes over time": "",
  "An eigenvalue that equals zero": "",
  "A degenerate eigenvalue means multiple linearly independent eigenstates share the same energy. This degeneracy often arises from symmetry in the system.": "",
  "What does the 'Hamiltonian matrix' represent in quantum mechanics?": "",
  "The probability distribution matrix": "",
  "The total energy operator whose eigenvalues are allowed energy levels": "",
  "The position operator": "",
  "The momentum operator": "",
  "The Hamiltonian H is the energy operator. Its eigenvalues E_n are the allowed energy levels, and its eigenvectors are the stationary states of the quantum system.": "",
  "What is a 'unitary matrix' and why is it important in quantum mechanics?": "",
  "A matrix with unit determinant; it represents measurement": "",
  "A matrix where U^dagger U = I; it represents time evolution preserving probabilities": "",
  "A diagonal matrix; it represents energy eigenstates": "",
  "A matrix with all entries equal to 1; it represents superposition": "",
  "A unitary matrix satisfies U^dagger U = I. In quantum mechanics, time evolution is unitary, meaning it preserves inner products and hence probabilities.": "",
  "What is the 'strain tensor' in continuum mechanics?": "",
  "A scalar measure of total deformation": "",
  "A symmetric matrix whose eigenvalues give the principal strains (stretches)": "",
  "The inverse of the stress tensor": "",
  "A vector describing the forces on a body": "",
  "The strain tensor is a symmetric matrix describing deformation. Its eigenvalues are the principal strains (maximum and minimum stretching), and eigenvectors are the principal strain directions.": "",
  "What does 'diagonalizing the Hamiltonian' mean physically?": "",
  "Removing the potential energy": "",
  "Reducing the system to one dimension": "",
  "Finding the energy eigenstates and energy levels of the system": "",
  "Making the system non-interacting": "",
  "Diagonalizing the Hamiltonian means finding a basis of energy eigenstates. In this basis, H is diagonal with energy eigenvalues on the diagonal, and each state evolves as e^(-iEt/h_bar).": "",
  "What is an 'Hermitian matrix' and why must physical observables be Hermitian?": "",
  "A matrix equal to its transpose; it ensures orthogonal eigenvectors": "",
  "A matrix equal to its conjugate transpose (A = A^dagger); it guarantees real eigenvalues (real measurement outcomes)": "",
  "A matrix with Hermitian symmetry along the diagonal; it ensures positive eigenvalues": "",
  "An invertible complex matrix; it ensures unique solutions": "",
  "An Hermitian matrix satisfies A = A^dagger. Physical observables must be Hermitian because measurement outcomes must be real numbers, and Hermitian matrices are guaranteed to have real eigenvalues.": "",
  "What is 'perturbation theory' in quantum mechanics as it relates to eigenvalues?": "",
  "A technique for approximating eigenvalues and eigenstates when a small perturbation is added to a solvable Hamiltonian": "",
  "A method to compute eigenvalues of large matrices numerically": "",
  "A method for diagonalizing infinite-dimensional matrices": "",
  "A way to remove degenerate eigenvalues from the spectrum": "",
  "Perturbation theory computes corrections to eigenvalues and eigenvectors when H = H0 + epsilon*V, where H0 is exactly solvable. First-order energy correction: E_n^(1) = <n|V|n>.": "",
  "A physicist models two coupled pendulums with stiffness matrix K = [[5, -1], [-1, 5]]. What are the normal mode frequencies and corresponding motions?": "",
  "omega = sqrt(5) for both modes": "",
  "omega = 5 (in-phase) and omega = 1 (out-of-phase)": "",
  "omega = sqrt(4) and omega = sqrt(4)": "",
  "omega = 2 (in-phase) and omega = sqrt(6) (out-of-phase)": "",
  "Eigenvalues: (5-lambda)^2 - 1 = 0, so lambda = 4 and 6. omega = sqrt(4) = 2 for eigenvector (1,1) (in-phase) and omega = sqrt(6) for (1,-1) (out-of-phase).": "",
  "A materials scientist analyzes the stress tensor sigma = [[8, 3], [3, 8]] MPa in a loaded plate. What are the principal stresses?": "",
  "11 MPa and 5 MPa": "",
  "8 MPa and 8 MPa": "",
  "3 MPa and 13 MPa": "",
  "10 MPa and 6 MPa": "",
  "det(sigma - lambda I) = (8-lambda)^2 - 9 = lambda^2 - 16lambda + 55 = (lambda - 11)(lambda - 5). The principal stresses are 11 MPa and 5 MPa, acting on planes rotated 45 degrees from the coordinate axes.": "",
  "A quantum computing researcher prepares a qubit in state |psi> = (1/sqrt(2))|0> + (1/sqrt(2))|1> and measures the Pauli-Z operator (eigenvalues +1, -1). What is the probability of getting +1?": "",
  "1/2": "",
  "1": "",
  "1/sqrt(2)": "",
  "The probability of measuring eigenvalue +1 is |<0|psi>|^2 = |1/sqrt(2)|^2 = 1/2. The state has equal amplitudes in both eigenstates, giving 50-50 measurement probabilities.": "",
  "An astrophysicist models the moment of inertia tensor of an asteroid as I = [[4, 0, 0], [0, 6, 2], [0, 2, 3]] kg*m^2. What is the smallest principal moment of inertia?": "",
  "2 kg*m^2": "",
  "3 kg*m^2": "",
  "4 kg*m^2": "",
  "1 kg*m^2": "",
  "One eigenvalue is 4 (from the 1,1 block). For the 2x2 block [[6,2],[2,3]]: trace=9, det=14, eigenvalues = (9 +/- sqrt(81-56))/2 = (9 +/- 5)/2 = 7 and 2. The smallest principal moment is 2 kg*m^2.": "",
  "A nuclear physicist models a two-level atomic system with Hamiltonian H = [[E0, V], [V, E0]] where E0 = 5 eV and V = 1 eV. What are the energy eigenvalues?": "",
  "3 eV and 7 eV": "",
  "5 eV and 5 eV": "",
  "5 eV and 1 eV": "",
  "4 eV and 6 eV": "",
  "For H = [[5,1],[1,5]], the eigenvalues are 5+1 = 6 and 5-1 = 4. The coupling V splits the degenerate level E0 into two levels separated by 2V = 2 eV.": "",
  "An optics researcher uses the Jones matrix J = [[cos(theta), -sin(theta)], [sin(theta), cos(theta)]] for theta = 45 degrees. The eigenvalues are e^(i*45 deg) and e^(-i*45 deg). What does this tell about the polarization?": "",
  "Circularly polarized eigenstates acquire a phase shift of +/-45 degrees": "",
  "Light is reflected at 45 degrees": "",
  "The matrix attenuates light by 45%": "",
  "Linearly polarized light rotates 90 degrees": "",
  "The eigenvectors of a rotation matrix are circularly polarized states (1, +/-i)/sqrt(2). Each acquires phase e^(+/-i*theta). This is the basis for circular birefringence.": "",
  "A geophysicist analyzes the seismic wave speed tensor in an anisotropic medium with C = [[5, 2], [2, 2]] (units: km^2/s^2). What are the fast and slow wave speeds?": "",
  "sqrt(6) km/s and 1 km/s": "",
  "3 km/s and sqrt(5) km/s": "",
  "sqrt(7) and sqrt(2) km/s": "",
  "5 km/s and 2 km/s": "",
  "Eigenvalues of C: trace = 7, det = 10 - 4 = 6. lambda = (7 +/- sqrt(49-24))/2 = (7 +/- 5)/2 = 6 and 1. Wave speeds are sqrt(eigenvalue): sqrt(6) approximately 2.45 km/s (fast) and 1 km/s (slow).": "",
  "A plasma physicist models charged particle motion in crossed E and B fields. The gyration is described by eigenvalues +/-i*omega_c where omega_c is the cyclotron frequency. What type of motion occurs?": "",
  "Circular orbit at the cyclotron frequency": "",
  "Exponential growth": "",
  "Linear motion along the magnetic field": "",
  "Exponential decay to rest": "",
  "Purely imaginary eigenvalues +/-i*omega_c produce circular motion (center-type solution). The particle gyrates around the magnetic field line at the cyclotron frequency omega_c = qB/m.": "",
  "A crystallographer analyzes the thermal vibration tensor U = [[0.05, 0.03], [0.03, 0.05]] (units: Angstrom^2). What are the principal amplitudes of vibration?": "",
  "0.03 and 0.07 Angstrom": "",
  "0.05 and 0.05 Angstrom": "",
  "sqrt(0.05) and sqrt(0.05) Angstrom": "",
  "sqrt(0.08) and sqrt(0.02) Angstrom, approximately 0.283 and 0.141": "",
  "Eigenvalues: (0.05-lambda)^2 - 0.0009 = 0, so lambda = 0.05 +/- 0.03 = 0.08 and 0.02. RMS amplitudes are sqrt(0.08) = 0.283 and sqrt(0.02) = 0.141 Angstrom. The larger vibration is along the (1,1) direction.": "",
  "A biophysicist models the diffusion of a protein in a cell membrane using the diffusion tensor D = [[3, 1], [1, 3]] (units: um^2/s). The eigenvalues are 4 and 2. Along which direction does the protein diffuse fastest?": "",
  "Along (1, 1)/sqrt(2), the diagonal direction": "",
  "Along (0, 1), the y-direction": "",
  "Along (1, 0), the x-direction": "",
  "Equally in all directions": "",
  "The fastest diffusion is along the eigenvector of the largest eigenvalue. For lambda=4: D-4I = [[-1,1],[1,-1]], giving (1,1). The protein diffuses fastest along the diagonal with diffusion constant 4 um^2/s.": ""
